footer: footer.title: {[Helvetica x 16]}{[8.0 x 10, 5.656 x 6]}{[normal x 16]}{[null x 16]} //^{a Estimated via ordinary least squares regression models adjusting for blocking and stratifciation variables (Hampden County geography, household} size and composition, gender of household head, and implementation wave); and respondent demographics (baseline age group, gender, and race/ ethnicity). Self-reported fruit and vegetable spending regressions additionally adjusted for usual reported intake measures from the EATS instrument; and baseline composite scale measures of availability of fruits and vegetables in the home; positive attitudes about foods, fruits, and vegetables; and perceived barriers to grocery shopping and to consumption of fruits and vegetables. All analyses incorporated sampling weights accounting for the unequal probability of respondent selection across strata, and for survey nonresponse if applicable. To account for respondents with more than one _{b follow-up observation, SEs and test statistics are heteroscedasticity-robust and clustered at the respondent level.} _{c Regression-adjusted mean intake.} Price elasticity calculated by dividing estimated impact expressed in proportional terms by the proportional change in the price of targeted fruits and _{d vegetables earning the HIP rebate (–0.3).} Boldface indicates whether difference in regression-adjusted means between HIP group and non-HIP group was statistically signifciant; two-sided _{e test: *p< 0.05; **p< 0.01; ***p< 0.001.} _{f} Outcome data from sampled respondent survey, primary shopper module, pooled early and late post-implementation sample (n=2,708). Outcome data from EBT transaction data, pooled across March–October 2012 (n=45,912 households per month). EBT, Electronic Beneft Transfer, HIP, Healthy Incentives Pilot; EATS, Eating at America’s Table Screener, TFV, targeted fruits and vegetables.
